1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,040
In this video, we will build the multi head attention block,

2

00:00:04,040  -->  00:00:07,960
the cornerstone component of our transformer model,

3

00:00:07,960  -->  00:00:11,840
and we will build it from scratch using PyTorch.

4

00:00:11,840  -->  00:00:18,480
I have to warn you that this will probably be the most involved part of the whole lesson,

5

00:00:18,480  -->  00:00:23,125
but the rest of the implementation for our model should be much easier.

6

00:00:23,125  -->  00:00:26,000
Before we start working on this implementation,

7

00:00:26,000  -->  00:00:29,620
we need to define a configuration for our model.

8

00:00:29,620  -->  00:00:32,750
This configuration will contain hyper parameters

9

00:00:32,750  -->  00:00:36,250
for our model that will define its structure.

10

00:00:36,250  -->  00:00:39,270
We will put this configuration into this dictionary,

11

00:00:39,270  -->  00:00:42,330
and here are the parameters that we will define.

12

00:00:42,330  -->  00:00:44,530
The first one is vocabulary_size,

13

00:00:44,530  -->  00:00:49,010
which is the size of the vocabulary defined by our tokenizer.

14

00:00:49,010  -->  00:00:53,280
This is a number of unique token IDs that it supports.

15

00:00:53,280  -->  00:00:56,265
The second parameter is context_size,

16

00:00:56,265  -->  00:00:59,040
which is the length of the context window.

17

00:00:59,040  -->  00:01:02,720
If you recall, this is the maximum number of tokens,

18

00:01:02,720  -->  00:01:04,820
our mode can see it once.

19

00:01:04,820  -->  00:01:07,250
The next parameter is embedding_dim,

20

00:01:07,250  -->  00:01:09,950
which is the size of embedding vectors.

21

00:01:09,950  -->  00:01:15,905
Each token in the input sequence will be converted to an embedding vector of this size.

22

00:01:15,905  -->  00:01:18,430
Next, we have the heads_num parameter,

23

00:01:18,430  -->  00:01:22,430
which is a number of attention heads we will have in our model.

24

00:01:22,430  -->  00:01:25,630
If you recall, we'll have multiple attention heads,

25

00:01:25,630  -->  00:01:28,945
and each will be processing input independently.

26

00:01:28,945  -->  00:01:31,945
Here we define how many of them we will have.

27

00:01:31,945  -->  00:01:36,790
Layers_num is a number of layers or transformer blocks in our model.

28

00:01:36,790  -->  00:01:42,150
The drop out rate is to configure how many outputs in drop out layers to set to zero.

29

00:01:42,150  -->  00:01:46,035
In the last parameter called use_bias is a Boolean flag

30

00:01:46,035  -->  00:01:50,850
indicating whether the linear transformations should include bias terms.

31

00:01:50,850  -->  00:01:53,950
We also need to compute the size of the output

32

00:01:53,950  -->  00:01:57,890
from each head to set dimensions of our model correctly.

33

00:01:57,890  -->  00:02:03,690
If you recall, every head produces output for only a part of each embedding vector.

34

00:02:03,690  -->  00:02:07,470
To calculate it, we divide the embedding vector size,

35

00:02:07,470  -->  00:02:09,110
by the number of heads,

36

00:02:09,110  -->  00:02:15,295
so all outputs from all heads together will produce a vector of the right size.

37

00:02:15,295  -->  00:02:19,130
Now, let's see how to implement a single attention head.

38

00:02:19,130  -->  00:02:20,810
To do this, we will define

39

00:02:20,810  -->  00:02:25,390
the attention head class that will implement a single attention head.

40

00:02:25,390  -->  00:02:28,390
To implement it, we need to inherit the module type and

41

00:02:28,390  -->  00:02:32,170
define a constructor where we define all building blocks.

42

00:02:32,170  -->  00:02:34,625
We first define matrices Q _weights,

43

00:02:34,625  -->  00:02:36,835
K_weights, and V_weights,

44

00:02:36,835  -->  00:02:41,350
and we will use them to convert input embedding vectors into Q,

45

00:02:41,350  -->  00:02:44,255
K, and V matrices correspondingly.

46

00:02:44,255  -->  00:02:46,570
We then define the dropout rate,

47

00:02:46,570  -->  00:02:49,380
and we define the casual attention mask.

48

00:02:49,380  -->  00:02:51,500
To define the attention mask,

49

00:02:51,500  -->  00:02:55,120
we first create a square matrix of the context window size,

50

00:02:55,120  -->  00:02:58,065
and we do it using the torch one function,

51

00:02:58,065  -->  00:03:04,100
and then we pass it to the true function to only get the values below the main diagonal.

52

00:03:04,100  -->  00:03:07,080
If you recall, this true function allows us to

53

00:03:07,080  -->  00:03:10,935
set all values above the main diagonal to zero.

54

00:03:10,935  -->  00:03:16,580
We then use the registered buffer method to save the casual attention mask.

55

00:03:16,580  -->  00:03:19,090
This function allows us to register

56

00:03:19,090  -->  00:03:22,770
a buffer that should not be considered a model parameter.

57

00:03:22,770  -->  00:03:26,530
But it won't be trained during the model training,

58

00:03:26,530  -->  00:03:29,240
but it would be part of a model state.

59

00:03:29,240  -->  00:03:31,910
Now having the constructor implemented,

60

00:03:31,910  -->  00:03:34,510
we will need to implement the forward method.

61

00:03:34,510  -->  00:03:36,750
In this method, we'll receive an input,

62

00:03:36,750  -->  00:03:41,240
which is a mini batch of converted input tokens.

63

00:03:41,240  -->  00:03:44,890
Throughout this method, I'll write these comments to

64

00:03:44,890  -->  00:03:48,310
specify the dimensions of different tensors,

65

00:03:48,310  -->  00:03:51,245
so we can keep track of what is going on.

66

00:03:51,245  -->  00:03:54,390
The input contains the following dimension.

67

00:03:54,390  -->  00:03:57,050
B is the size of a mini batch,

68

00:03:57,050  -->  00:03:59,750
C is the size of a context window,

69

00:03:59,750  -->  00:04:03,270
and embedding_dim is the size of an embedding vector.

70

00:04:03,270  -->  00:04:07,015
Using this input, we can compute matrices Q, K,

71

00:04:07,015  -->  00:04:10,130
and V correspondingly, using our Q_weights,

72

00:04:10,130  -->  00:04:11,865
K_weights, and V_weights.

73

00:04:11,865  -->  00:04:18,270
Each of the separation will produce separate tensors of size B by C by head_size.

74

00:04:18,270  -->  00:04:20,700
Now, having matrices Q and K,

75

00:04:20,700  -->  00:04:24,500
we need to multiply them to compute attention scores.

76

00:04:24,500  -->  00:04:26,520
To multiply them, however,

77

00:04:26,520  -->  00:04:29,500
we first need to transpose matrix Q

78

00:04:29,500  -->  00:04:33,585
so to make sure that we're doing the.product correctly.

79

00:04:33,585  -->  00:04:35,760
As a result of this multiplication,

80

00:04:35,760  -->  00:04:38,540
we will get a new tensor with dimensions P,

81

00:04:38,540  -->  00:04:44,050
which is specialized by C by C. Then having the attention scores,

82

00:04:44,050  -->  00:04:46,990
we need to apply the casual attention mask.

83

00:04:46,990  -->  00:04:50,810
To do so use the mask fill method that will set

84

00:04:50,810  -->  00:04:55,310
the positions where the mask is zero to negative infinity.

85

00:04:55,310  -->  00:05:00,990
This will allow us to ignore these positions in the subsequent softmax step.

86

00:05:00,990  -->  00:05:06,220
Then we also need to scale the attention scores as we've discussed before.

87

00:05:06,220  -->  00:05:09,850
To do this, we divide it by the square root of the K,

88

00:05:09,850  -->  00:05:12,670
which is the size of queries and keys.

89

00:05:12,670  -->  00:05:18,220
The scaling allows us to make sure that attention scores don't become too large.

90

00:05:18,220  -->  00:05:21,150
Finally, we will apply the softmax function to

91

00:05:21,150  -->  00:05:25,190
the attention scores to convert the scores to probabilities,

92

00:05:25,190  -->  00:05:27,290
ensuring they sum up to one.

93

00:05:27,290  -->  00:05:30,010
We then multiply the attention scores and

94

00:05:30,010  -->  00:05:33,970
V matrix to calculate new embedding vector values.

95

00:05:33,970  -->  00:05:38,310
But we also need to apply the dropout to avoid overfitting.

96

00:05:38,310  -->  00:05:41,430
Now, let's quickly test if it all works together.

97

00:05:41,430  -->  00:05:46,280
To do this, I'll create a random input tensor with a batch size of 8,

98

00:05:46,280  -->  00:05:48,000
the context window size,

99

00:05:48,000  -->  00:05:51,180
and the embedding dimensionality that we will use,

100

00:05:51,180  -->  00:05:54,720
and we'll use this input to test our attention head.

101

00:05:54,720  -->  00:05:56,220
Now, to use this input,

102

00:05:56,220  -->  00:06:00,520
we'll instantiate the attention head class using our configuration,

103

00:06:00,520  -->  00:06:05,460
and then we'll pass this input tensor through the attention head to get some output.

104

00:06:05,460  -->  00:06:10,960
Of course, passing random data through an interim model will return gibberish.

105

00:06:10,960  -->  00:06:15,880
But what we can do, we can test that the outputs have the right dimensions.

106

00:06:15,880  -->  00:06:17,840
If we look at the dimensions,

107

00:06:17,840  -->  00:06:19,200
we see that there are eight,

108

00:06:19,200  -->  00:06:25,020
which is our mini batch size that we selected by the context size by 64,

109

00:06:25,020  -->  00:06:29,220
and 64 is actually the head size that we've calculated

110

00:06:29,220  -->  00:06:33,440
here using the embeddings dimensions and the number of heads.

111

00:06:33,440  -->  00:06:37,580
Now, so far, we only have a single attention head implemented.

112

00:06:37,580  -->  00:06:43,070
Now we can implement multi head attention that combines multiple heads together.

113

00:06:43,070  -->  00:06:47,310
To implement it, we again inherit from the module type.

114

00:06:47,310  -->  00:06:53,170
We then create a list of attention head instances and we store them in this module list.

115

00:06:53,170  -->  00:06:58,645
We also define an additional linear layer that will apply to each embedding vector.

116

00:06:58,645  -->  00:07:02,780
Then we add another drop out layer for regularization.

117

00:07:02,780  -->  00:07:06,650
Now, to implement the forward method, we first of all,

118

00:07:06,650  -->  00:07:09,910
pass our input through all of our heads,

119

00:07:09,910  -->  00:07:15,030
and then we get outputs from each one of these heads and store them into heads outputs.

120

00:07:15,030  -->  00:07:18,730
We then concatenate the outputs along the last dimension,

121

00:07:18,730  -->  00:07:21,510
and then we pass the results through the linear layer,

122

00:07:21,510  -->  00:07:24,470
and we apply and drop out to the final output.

123

00:07:24,470  -->  00:07:28,650
Now, that's it. That's the whole multi head attention block implemented.

124

00:07:28,650  -->  00:07:30,330
Now we will instantiate

125

00:07:30,330  -->  00:07:34,650
this multi head attention class using our configuration dictionary,

126

00:07:34,650  -->  00:07:37,450
and we pass the same input tensor through

127

00:07:37,450  -->  00:07:40,470
the multi head attention block to get the output.

128

00:07:40,470  -->  00:07:42,990
Now, if you look at the shape of the output,

129

00:07:42,990  -->  00:07:46,450
you will see that it looks similar to what we had before,

130

00:07:46,450  -->  00:07:51,010
but now the size of the last dimension is 768,

131

00:07:51,010  -->  00:07:54,560
which is also the size of our embedding vectors.

132

00:07:54,560  -->  00:08:00,180
This means that we were able to create multi head attention with multiple heads,

133

00:08:00,180  -->  00:08:04,310
pass the inputs through different heads and combine them together.

134

00:08:04,310  -->  00:08:07,130
Now the size of the output is the same as

135

00:08:07,130  -->  00:08:10,950
the size of the input we passed to the multi head attention.

136

00:08:10,950  -->  00:08:14,730
Now, that's it. Now we have implemented multi head attention,

137

00:08:14,730  -->  00:08:18,730
and now using this, we can build the rest of our model.
